<p>Speakers in the past have included the Hon’ble President of India A P J Abdul Kalam, Prof Kevin ‘Cyborg’ Warwick, Dr K. Kasturirangan (ex-Chief, ISRO), Dr. Ponani Gopalkrishnan (Head, IBM Research Labs, India),   Dr Stephen Wolfram (Creator of ‘Mathematica’), Mr. Narayanmurthy, Sir Roger Penrose, Mr. Rajat Gupta, Mr. Richard Stallman, media guru Alyque Padamsee and Dr. Jayant Narlikar among others.</p>
<h1>Competitions</h1>
<p><img src="./img/survivor.gif" hspace=10 vspace=5 align="right">Competitions form the backbone of Techfest – the largest of all the events! In every edition, the competitions have become tougher but have been met with an even greater response from participants. At Techfest’s Competitions participants are pit against the best minds in the country, and with prizes of over 6 lacs to be won, stakes run high.</p><br>
<p>  A brief look at the competitions in the previous years :</p>
<h3>Survivor -The International Challenge </h3>
<p>The challenge was to build a wireless robot that climbs an inclined plane, survives a 1 metre fall, completes a prescribed task and then follows a line autonomously all in competition with another participant’s machine.  </p>
<h3>Micromouse</h3>
<p>Make your machine navigate through a standard maze, all by itself, as fast as possible! Techfest 2005 witnessed the completion of the maze in a whopping 17 seconds. Also teams from Iran placed 2nd and 4th in Micromouse 2005.</p>
<h3>Drishti</h3>
<p>A competition to develop aids for the blind. In association with the National Association for the Blind (NAB), this was a first step taken by Techfest 2005. We hope to continue in this direction and make giving back to society a tradition of Techfest.</p>
<h3>Chemsplash </h3>
<p>Chemicals and chemical engineering galore! Chemsplash at Techfest has always sought for out-of-the-box thinking related to Chemical Engineering, through competitions like <strong>Chem-e-Car</strong>, which involved making a completely chemically powered car which could traverse certain distance, based on certain constraints such as going a certain distance and completely coming to a halt, or completing a given distance in the shortest time possible . <strong>U-Turn </strong>at Techfest 2005 involved such cars to go a distance of 10 metres and come back to the starting point with the best possible accuracy.  In 2005, Chemsplash came up with the innovative and spontaneous <strong>“Dexter’s Den”</strong> which invited mathematical models from participants and demanded there implementation within two days, after 3 different on-the-spot problem statements were posed on the first morning of the fest.</p>
<h3>Last Straw</h3>
<p><img src="./img/laststraw.gif" hspace=10  vspace=5 align="left">Civil engineering beckons… hair-tearing problem statements that demand you to make complex structures using simple, commonly available materials like straws, popsicle sticks, thermocol and so on…</p>
<strong>Open Events</strong>
<i>Open Software, Open Hardware, Open Design</i>
<p>Events that have no constraints on what to create or design - the only criteria of judging are their usefulness and applicability – anything that makes life simpler! 
</p><br>
<p>Pre defined challenges like <strong>Contraption, Anaconda, Udaan, Decathlon, Atlantis.</strong></p>
<h1>Hub and Exhibitions</h1>
<p><img src="./img/hubgif.gif" hspace=10  vspace=5 align="right">The Hub – an extremely well suited toponym is the place buzzing with activity throughout Techfest. Informal on-the-spot competitions, which test spontaneity and creativity, are the big draws at The Hub. Teasing and interesting problem statements have been met with equally ingenious solutions. Prizes are also aplenty in the form of T-Shirts, caps and books. Apart from this, the Hub also has its own lectures, documentaries and logic quizzes. </p><br>
<p>Exhibitions at Techfest have always left the viewers exhilarated. On display are some of the latest innovations and breakthrough technology. Past exhibitions have included</p><br>
<strong>R&D Exhibition </strong>(’05 & ’03) – Showcasing the latest in cutting-edge technologies.<br><br>
<strong>Navy Exhibition </strong>in Techfest 2004 – the first exhibition of its size and kind held at a venue other than a naval dockyard by the Indian Navy.<br><br>
<strong>IAF Para-jumping exhibition (2004)</strong>held on Jan 26th to commemorate Republic Day& Air Force Exhibition (2002).<br>
